Notes.Title: Paravirtualization Concept
Notes.Content: Paravirtualization involves modifying the guest operating system (OS) to interact with the hypervisor (host OS) and hardware more efficiently. It differs from full virtualization by allowing the guest OS to be aware of the virtualization and to interact directly with the hypervisor. This approach enhances performance by reducing the overhead associated with traditional virtualization techniques.
Notes.Wrong_Content: Paravirtualization involves modifying the guest operating system (OS) to interact with the host OS and hardware more efficiently. It is similar to but different from other virtualization techniques, focusing on reducing costs associated with virtualization.

Notes.Title: Emulators and Containers
Notes.Content: Emulators, such as CPU emulators, allow different types of CPU to run applications designed for other platforms. An example is the 佐天堂 CPU. Containers are not virtual machines (VMs); instead, they are a lightweight form of virtualization that shares the host OS kernel, allowing applications to run in isolated environments without the overhead of full VM instances.
Notes.Wrong_Content: Emulators such as CPU emulators, specifically mentioned as 佐天堂 CPU, allow different types of CPU to run applications designed for other platforms. Containers are described as lightweight virtual machines (VMs) that also aim to reduce costs.
